    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1943-11-04T11:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1943-11-04T11:00:00-05:00" n="437"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d437">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">740.00116 European War 1939/1142: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in the United Kingdom</hi> (<persName
                        type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Winant</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">London</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1943-11-04T17:00:00+01:00"
                            >November 4, 1943—5 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received November 4—1:15 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>7652. Reference Embassy’s 7239, October 21, 1 p.m. This morning’s <hi
                        rend="italic">Daily Sketch</hi> carried a brief item to the effect that the
                    Soviet Government had appointed a representative to the United Nations
                    Commission for the Investigation of War Crimes and that this altered its
                    previous decision not to be represented.</p>
                <p>A high official of the Foreign Office has informed the Embassy that as far as he
                    is aware the situation has not changed from that previously reported and that
                    negotiations are still in progress with the Soviet Government on this question.
                    He expressed the opinion that the author of the item in the <hi rend="italic"
                        >Daily Sketch</hi> had misinterpreted the meaning of the Moscow declaration
                    on punishment of German war criminals.<note n="30" xml:id="d437fn30">For text of
                        declaration, see <ref target="#pg_768">p. 768</ref>.</note> The Foreign
                    Office will keep the Embassy informed of developments.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Winant</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
